'''Anne L. Poulet''' (born March 20, 1942) is a retired [[United States|American]] [[art historian]]. Poulet is an expert in the area of [[French art]], particularly [[sculpture]]. In her career, she organized two major monographic exhibitions on the [[France|French]] sculptors [[Clodion]] and [[Jean-Antoine Houdon]], respectively.

==Career==
Poulet received a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] degree from [[Sweet Briar College]], a private [[Women's colleges in the United States|all women's college]] in [[Sweet Briar, Virginia]], in 1964 and graduated [[Latin honors|cum laude]]. She then completed her graduate studies at the [[New York University Institute of Fine Arts]] in 1970.

After serving for twenty years as curator in the department of decorative arts and sculpture at the [[Museum of Fine Arts, Boston]], she was appointed the director of [[The Frick Collection]] in October 2003. She became the first female director in the museum's history. She retired in 2011 and was succeeded by Ian Wardropper.<ref>http://www.frick.org/sites/default/files/pdf/press/AnnePoulet2010_archived.pdf</ref>

Joined the Institute of Fine Arts' Board of Trustees at NYU in September of 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=//www.nyu.edu/gsas/dept/fineart/news/archive.htm|title=News Archive|last=|first=|date=March 9, 2018|website=New York University|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>

==Honors==
*[[Chevalier dans l'Ordre des Arts et des Lettres]], [[France]] (2007)<ref>https://www.nyu.edu/gsas/dept/fineart/pdfs/press/Anne-Poulet-2011.pdf</ref>

