The '''Emites''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|ɛ|m|aɪ|t|s}} or {{IPAc-en|ˈ|iː|m|aɪ|t|s}}) or '''Emim''' ([[Hebrew]]: אֵמִים) was the [[Moabite language|Moabite]] name for [[Rephaim]]. They are described in [[Deuteronomy]] chapter 2 as having been a powerful and populous people. They were defeated by the [[Moab|Moabite]]s, who occupied their land. The Emim are also mentioned in [[Book of Genesis|Genesis]] {{bibleverse-nb||Genesis|14:5|HE}} and according to [[Rashi]], the name is translated as "the dreaded ones" (Hertz 1936) and the singular Ema/Emma (Hebrew: אימה) means "horror" or "terror".
{{quote|The Emims dwelt therein in times past, a people great, and many, and tall, as the [[Anakim]].|{{bibleverse||Deuteronomy|2:10-11|HE}}}}
They are the subject of [[John Darnielle]]/[[The Mountain Goats]]'s single "Deuteronomy 2:10."
==References== *J.H. Hertz (1936) The Pentateuch and Haftoras. Deuteronomy. Oxford, Oxford University Press.
