===Calendar===
{{Muslimmonths}}
{{Main|Islamic calendar}}
[[File:Lunar libration with phase Oct 2007.gif|thumb|left|The phases of the [[Moon]] form the basis for the [[Islamic calendar]]]]
The formal beginning of the Muslim era was chosen, reportedly by [[Umar|Caliph Umar]], to be the [[Hijra (Islam)|Hijra]] in 622 CE, which was an important turning point in Muhammad's fortunes. It is a [[lunar calendar]] with days lasting from sunset to sunset.<ref>[[Patheos Library]] – Islam Sacred Time – [http://www.patheos.com/Library/Islam/Ritual-Worship-Devotion-Symbolism/Sacred-Time.html Patheos.com]</ref> Islamic [[Muslim holidays|holy days]] fall on fixed dates of the lunar calendar, which means that they occur in [[seasons|different seasons]] in different years in the [[Gregorian calendar]]. The most important Islamic festivals are ''[[Eid al-Fitr]]'' ({{lang-ar|عيد الفطر}}) on the 1st of ''[[Shawwal]]'', marking the end of the fasting month ''Ramadan'', and ''[[Eid al-Adha]]'' ({{lang|ar|عيد الأضحى}}) on the 10th of ''[[Dhu al-Hijjah]]'', coinciding with the end of the Hajj pilgrimage.<ref>Ghamidi (2001): [http://www.renaissance.com.pk/janisla2y2.html Customs and Behavioral Laws] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130923142412/http://www.renaissance.com.pk/janisla2y2.html |date=2013-09-23 }}</ref>

